# DDTree Path B — decouple RoPE phase from KV slot index

_Follow-up to Path A reverted in ecbc49d + corruption confirmed in 6c84b13
(2026-04-23). Unblocks DDTree slow-path kill._

## ⚠️ CATASTROPHIC FAILURE SURFACE — READ BEFORE TOUCHING CODE ⚠️

Path B touches the K projection / RoPE / KV-write hot path on the
production tree-verify forward. Subtle bugs HIDE behind plausible-looking
metrics — Path A was reverted only after we eyeballed the actual decoded
tokens, because the bug presented as "+120% tok/s, +79% τ, sd=0.15".

The failure mode is **degenerate token attractor**: model locks into
predicting the same token over and over because RoPE / K phase skew
warps attention into a fixed-point basin. Every metric likes this:
- 100% draft acceptance (draft trivially matches target's repeated token)
- High τ (mean accepted per cycle ≫ 5)
- LOW stddev (deterministic loop)
- High tok/s (no slow-path fires once stuck)

The output is `numbers(numbers(numbers(...)` forever. Pure-stat gates
(speed-gate, τ-gate, even coherence-gate's PPL check on short outputs)
**do not catch this**. Only an eyeball or token-distribution check does.

**Mandatory guards for every Path B iteration**:

1. **Token-distribution check after every smoke**:
   - Decode 256 emitted tokens
   - Assert `unique_token_count / total > 0.3`
   - Assert `max_token_frequency / total < 0.4`
   - If either fails → STOP, you have a bug, do NOT trust τ
2. **Eyeball decoded text** for at least one prose, one code, one
   instruct prompt before claiming a win.
3. **3-prompt smoke before any commit**: run prose / code / instruct
   end-to-end, dump first 200 chars of output to stderr, visually scan.
4. Speed-gate / quality-gate runs are NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT.

**Do not commit Path B changes that have not passed the eyeball check.**
A "great metrics, garbage output" commit can and will be cargo-culted
into release before someone notices.

This trap is also why the GdnTape / kv_gather scaffolding shipped in
ecbc49d is gated to opt-in via env vars when re-enabled — it should
remain opt-in until Path B applies the per-commit RoPE rotation.

## Why this exists

DDTree-batched on 27B asym3 hits 35-50% slow-path cycles on prose / instruct (per
HIPFIRE_DDTREE_TAPE_DUMP). Each fires a full re-verify (~40-50 ms) that we'd like
to replace with a cheap KV / tape gather (~0.5 ms). Path A tried the gather-only
fix and reverted because:

> Tree verify writes K with RoPE phase baked in for the LINEARIZATION slot
> (`qwen35.rs:3048-3067` — "flat linear start_pos..start_pos+n"). Byte-wise
> gathering K from `start_pos + 1 + acc[j-1]` into the committed slot
> `start_pos + j` moves the bytes but leaves the baked RoPE phase stale.

Path B fixes this structurally: tree verify writes K either (a) without RoPE so
RoPE can be applied later at commit time, or (b) with a rope_phase array that's
INDEPENDENT of the kv_slot index, so the "right" phase can be chosen based on
where the committed slot will land.

Both options require splitting one `positions` array (currently doing double
duty) into two — `rope_phase[i]` and `kv_slot_index[i]` — and threading both
through the FA dispatch.

## Two implementation variants

## ⚠️ STRUCTURAL DEAD-END FOUND (2026-04-23, commit f9c920a) ⚠️

Phase 1 + Phase 2 implemented. Phase 2 produces the same `numbers(
numbers(numbers(...)` token attractor as Path A on code, caught
correctly by the dflash coherence battery (commit 9883e98).

**Root cause** (only obvious in hindsight, validated by composing
two memories — `project_k_kernel_head256_fix.md` and
`feedback_attention_precision.md`):

Tree-mode FA attention uses **linearization slot deltas** for
relative position phase (RoPE):
  - Tree node at linear slot i, attending to linear slot j ⇒
    Q · K depends on `(i - j)` via RoPE.
  - For accepted nodes [0, 1, 4, 5] this gives deltas [1, 3, 1].

A linear forward on the same accepted tokens would use
**committed slot deltas**:
  - Accepted i, committed at slot i, attending to committed slot
    i-1 ⇒ delta = 1 every step.
  - For [0, 1, 4, 5] committed at [0, 1, 2, 3] this gives [1, 1, 1].

These are **different relative position phases** → different attention
scores → different FA output → different wqkv input → different K
post-projection. The pre-RoPE K we capture in tree mode is ALREADY
poisoned by the upstream FA's use of wrong relative phases.

Per `feedback_attention_precision.md`: **5% attention error is fatal
under greedy decode** — cascades into a token-attractor loop within
~10 tokens. Our K isn't off by 5% per se, but the per-position phase
delta error compounds across layers and cycles.

**No per-commit RoPE rotation on the gathered K can fix this** — the
problem is that tree-mode FA's *upstream* attention computation used
the wrong phase deltas, poisoning everything downstream of that FA
layer. Path B Variant B1 was designed assuming K is the only thing
that needs phase correction. It isn't.

### Updated viable paths

1. **FA-only re-verify** (likely best). Skip FFN + LM head + tape
   replay. Run a real linear forward through every FA layer on the
   committed chain, which gives K at correct phases. ~50% savings vs
   full re-verify. Doesn't need decoupled RoPE/KV-slot at all.
2. **Pipeline the slow path with the next draft cycle** (Task #93 —
   inter-cycle pipelining). Slow path's wall cost stays the same but
   gets hidden behind the next draft.
3. **Run tree FA with committed-equivalent positions a priori** —
   impossible without knowing the accept chain ahead of time.
4. **Switch tree attention to depth-based phases** (paper scheme) —
   restores per-position-phase consistency with committed slots BUT
   re-introduces sibling KV-write race (which the linearization
   scheme was solving).

Path B1 is closed. Phase 1 + 2 code stays in-tree env-gated as
the historical record / instructive failure. The pre_rope_k
infrastructure could be reused IF we ever pursue option 1 (FA-only
re-verify can use the captured pre-RoPE K to skip wqkv too — saving
~5-10% more on top of the FA-skip).

---

### B1 — Pre-RoPE K storage + post-commit RoPE pass (CHOSEN — but FAILED, see above)

- Tree verify dispatches FA with `rope_phase = position + linear_idx` (current)
  AND stores **pre-RoPE K (F32)** in a per-tree-verify scratch buffer
  sized `big_n × n_kv_heads × head_dim × 4` bytes per FA layer
  (~52 KB per FA layer × ~16 FA layers on 27B = ~830 KB total).
- Post-commit, in slow path:
  1. Tape gather (existing scaffolding from ecbc49d)
  2. Per FA layer: gather pre-RoPE K rows from scratch by
     `accepted_node_indices[j]+1` into a contiguous `[accept_len+1] × n_kv_heads × head_dim`
     buffer (and seed at index 0 — already correct linearly)
  3. Apply existing `rope_partial_interleaved_f32_batched` with positions
     `[position + 0, position + 1, ..., position + accept_len]` (committed
     phases — the right ones) to the gathered K rows
  4. Re-quant + write to `kv_cache[position .. position + accept_len + 1]`
     using the existing `kv_cache_write_*_batched` kernels
  5. Replay GDN tape (existing)
- Pros: reuses existing RoPE + kv_write kernels — no new HIP kernels needed
  for B1 itself. Just orchestration + scratch.
- Cons: doubles K storage cost during tree verify. V doesn't need this
  treatment (no RoPE on V).
- **Pre-RoPE K capture means we tap fa_k_batch BEFORE the
  rope_partial_interleaved kernel runs in qwen35.rs:3468. That kernel
  rotates K in-place. A separate memcpy_dtod into the scratch BEFORE
  the RoPE call captures the pre-RoPE state.**

### B2 — Two-array FA kernel

- FA kernel takes `rope_phase: &[i32]` AND `kv_slot_index: &[i32]` as
  separate args. RoPE rotates Q/K with `rope_phase[i]`. KV cache write
  uses `kv_slot_index[i]`. Tree verify sets:
  - `rope_phase[i] = position + i` (current, keeps RoPE distinct per tree node)
  - `kv_slot_index[i] = position + i` (current, distinct slot per tree node)
- Tree verify path is BIT-IDENTICAL to today (both arrays equal).
- Slow-path kill becomes a pure byte gather BUT we need to ALSO somehow
  apply the right RoPE — defeats the purpose unless paired with a per-commit
  rotate.
- Worse than B1 unless we also build the rotate kernel — at which point we
  might as well do B1 instead.

**Pick B1.** B2 buys nothing on its own.

## Implementation scope (B1)

### New kernels (~150 LOC HIP)

`kernels/src/kv_apply_rope_post_gather.hip`:
```c
__global__ void kv_apply_rope_post_gather_f16(
    const __half* k_pre_rope,       // [n_positions × n_kv_heads × head_dim]
    __half*       k_cache_out,      // sub-view at slot `dst_base`
    const i32*    src_indices,      // [n_positions] — read pre_rope row src_indices[i]
    const i32*    rope_positions,   // [n_positions] — apply RoPE phase for these
    int n_kv_heads, int head_dim,
    float rope_theta,
    int dst_base                    // start writing at kv_cache[dst_base × bpp]
);
```

Plus a quantized variant for asym3/4/2 K (more involved — RoPE must precede
Givens rotation + quantization). Likely a separate kernel per quant mode.
Order: ship F16 first as proof, then port to asym3.

### qwen35.rs changes (~100 LOC)

- Tree verify branch: when `tree_verify.is_some()`, allocate a per-cycle
  pre-RoPE K scratch (or take it from PrefillBatchScratch), dispatch the
  existing wqkv kernel WITHOUT applying RoPE to K (probably via a flag arg
  or a new kernel entry point — needs to look at gemm_qkv kernel surface),
  and store the K rows.
- Apply RoPE inline (current behavior) for Q only — Q's phase is the live
  query position, no problem.
- Keep the existing kv_cache_write_* call unchanged: it still writes K at
  `kv_slot_index = position + i` so that later cycles read the gathered K.

### speculative.rs changes (~50 LOC + revert un-revert)

- Reapply the `gather_accepted` slow-path branch I shipped in ecbc49d (the
  scaffolding is still there, currently unused).
- Add a step between tape gather and replay: dispatch the
  `kv_apply_rope_post_gather` kernel per FA layer, reading from the new
  pre-RoPE K scratch with `src_indices = [position, position+1+acc[0],
  position+1+acc[1], ...]` and `rope_positions = [position+0, position+1,
  position+2, ...]` (the committed-chain phases).

### dflash_spec_demo.rs (~5 LOC)

- Allocate the pre-RoPE K scratch alongside DdtreeScratch (or fold into it).

## Speed / quality gates

**Speed gate (regression ≤ noise on existing paths):**
- 27B linear asym3 HumanEval n=33 within ±5% of pre-fix mean (128 tok/s).
- 27B fast-path-only DDTree b12-k2 asym3 prose (force_slow=0 condition) within
  ±5% of pre-fix mean.

**Speed gate (slow-path kill must move the needle):**
- 27B b12-k2 asym3 prose: ≥ +15% mean tok/s vs pre-fix (76 → 87+ tok/s) on
  3-run mean to defeat ksplit-atomic variance.
- 27B b12-k2 asym3 instruct: ≥ +10% mean tok/s vs pre-fix (70 → 77+ tok/s).
- 27B b12-k2 asym3 code (HumanEval n=33): mean tok/s within −5% of pre-fix
  (84 → 80+ tok/s) — code is mostly fast-path so no big lift expected.

**Quality gate:**
- Coherence-gate on prose + instruct + code at b12-k2 + asym3.
- HumanEval n=33 mean τ within ±0.3 of pre-fix (5.39 mean).
- Spot-check: 5 prose runs, no degenerate token-loop output.

## Sequencing

1. F16 prototype kernel + dispatch (3-4 hours): un-revert speculative.rs gather
   path, add F16 KV-only branch in qwen35.rs, wire pre-RoPE scratch. Smoke on
   F16 KV mode (which we don't normally use but is the cheapest path to validate
   the design before touching quantized kernels).
2. Asym3 quant variant (4-6 hours): port the post-gather RoPE kernel to operate
   on asym3 K. Validate Givens rotation + 3-bit quantization composition.
3. Other quant modes (asym2, asym4, q8) — port in parallel once asym3 works.
4. Speed/quality gate sweep + commit.

Total: ~1-2 days of focused engineering.

## Rollback

All changes are inside `if tree_verify.is_some()` branches and the slow-path
of `spec_step_ddtree_batched`. A bad result reverts cleanly to today's
behavior (full re-verify). Path A scaffolding stays untouched.

## Out of scope

- Multi-arch testing (BC-250, V620, MI300X) — gfx1100 first.
- Generalizing decouple to AR-decode path — DDTree-only for now.
- Path B2 (two-array FA without per-commit rotate) — strictly worse than B1.
- Per-genre dispatch policy work (handled separately in
  `ddtree-b12k2-asym3-prose-instruct-win.prd`).
